dv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="sasiaz"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Southern Asia</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:india"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="seasiaz"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Southeast Asia</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:singp"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Home</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">HOME IN FOCUS; A work of devotion: Little India temple gets $4m facelift</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Iconic Little India temple gets $4m facelift; now boasts new facilities and brighter spaces</Para><Para>For more than a year, devotees at the 164-year-old Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple have been sharing sacred space with 20 artisans and a score of other workmen.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Scaffolding towers over their heads as they stream into the main temple hall and bright blue canvas sheets and grey debris netting block off sections undergoing delicate restoration works.</Para><Para>The iconic temple in Little India, one of the oldest in Singapore, is being restored to the tune of some $4 million. This is the fourth time renovations have been undertaken since it was declared a National Monument by the Preservation of Monuments Board in 1978.</Para><Para>And the task is by no means a small one. Successive management committees have worked to abide by its conservation status, for instance, by keeping to the colour scheme of the original temple.</Para><Para>A chief sculptor and a team of 19 highly skilled artisans were flown in from India for the job.</Para><Para>They painstakingly match every shade, bending over intricate carvings and arching back to apply a veritable rainbow of colours to the temple's vast ceiling. They go about their craft silently, hardly noticing the ongoing life around the temple.</Para><Para>This is one of the biggest challenges the restoration team faces - accommodating the various rituals, festivals and ceremonies while the extensive work is being done.</Para><Para>*</Para><Para>$4m</Para><Para>Estimated cost of restoration project at the 164-year-old Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple, one of the oldest Hindu temples in Singapore.</Para><Para>20</Para><Para>Number of highly skilled artisans from India who were flown to Singapore to carry out the restoration works.</Para><Para>2</Para><Para>Approximate number of years it takes to plan for a consecration ceremony and the temple's redevelopment.</Para><Para>As Dr Vellayappan Karruppiah, 73, chairman of the temple, put it: "This is a living monument."</Para><Para>He said: "Every day, there are poojas going on and major festivals during which the work has to stop. The management committee has to plan so the work can be finished in time, and I am happy to say that we are on schedule."</Para><Para>Restoration and resanctification of Hindu temples here are carried out every 12 years. The last three redevelopment works for the Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple were in 1979, 1992 and 2005. The Hindu Endowments Board funds the works and appeals for donations are made to supplement the cost.</Para><Para>Mr Kanapathy Satthaiyah paints on the ceiling of the Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple, which is ornamented with sculpted images portraying colourful floral motifs, on Jan 5, 2018. ST PHOTO: LIM YAOHUI</Para><Para>The current renovations include making more space for devotees to worship and eat in, improving ventilation and lighting, and facilities like bathrooms and walkways. Paintings, murals and religious motifs are repainted, while structures like the rajagopuram (tower entrance), pillars and vimanams (temple roof) are reconditioned. A new multi-purpose facility for blessed meals and religious ceremonies has also been added.</Para><Para>At the end of the restoration process, an elaborate ceremony for the resanctification of the temple will be conducted by 39 priests. This is when the sculptures of the deities will be moved into the newly renovated space. The Hindu almanac has yielded an auspicious date for the celebrations - April 22.</Para><Para>Rare sacred ceremonies will be performed over about five months. It is believed the rituals will bring goodness and prosperity to the devotees, community and nation.</Para><Para>The temple's devotees are looking forward to the consecration ceremony. Dental surgery assistant Santhi Rajasaker, 45, who goes to the temple at least three times a month, said : "I'm glad to see the temple undergoing renovation and looking forward to see its new appearance."</Para><Para>After the noon prayers, blessed food is served to devotees by temple volunteers, while restoration works are still in progress, at Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple on March 3, 2018. ST PHOTO: LIM YAOHUI</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Lim YaohuiPhotojournalist </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Artisan Vaithi Ganesh, 40, adding the final touches to an arch embellished with an image of a yali – a mythical creature believed to protect and guard temples and ways leading to them. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

